tors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA place comes into existence through the depth of relationships that underwrite a physical location with layers of sedimented names. In Place Matters scholars and artists conduct varied forms of place-based inquiry to demonstrate why place matters. Lavishly illustrated, the volume brings into conversation photographic projects and essays that revitalize the study of landscape.Contributors engage the study of place through an approach that Jonathan Bordo and Blake Fitzpatrick call critical topography: the way that we understand critical thought to range over a place, or how thought and symbolic forms invent place through text and image as if initiated by an X marking the spot. Critical topography’s tasks are to mediate and to diminish the gap between representation and referent, to be both in the world and about the world; to ask what place is this, what are its names, where am I, how and with what responsibilities may I be here? Chapters map the deep cultural, environmental, and political histories of singular places, interrogating the charged relation between history, place, and power and identifying the territorial imperatives of place making in such sites as Colonus, Mont Sainte-Victoire, Chomolungma/Everest, Hiroshima, Fort Qu’Appelle, Donetsk airport, and the island of Lesbos. With contributions from the renowned artists Hamish Fulton and Edward Burtynsky, the Swedish poet Jesper Svenbro, and others, the collection examines profound shifts in place-based thinking as it relates to the history of art, the anthropocene and nuclear ruin, borders and global migration, residential schools, the pandemic, and sites of refuge.In his prologue W.J.T. Mitchell writes: “Places, like feasts, are moveable. They can be erased and forgotten, lost in space, or maintained and rebuilt. Both their appearance and disappearance, their making and unmaking, are the work of critical topography.” Global in scope, Canadian in spirit, and grounded in singular sites, Place Matters presents critical topography as an approach to analyze, interpret, and reflect on place.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGeocriticismvCongresses. 0aGeocriticism. 0aLandscapes in artvCongresses. 0aLandscapes in art. 0aPlace (Philosophy) in artvCongresses. 0aPlace (Philosophy) in art. 0aPlace (Philosophy) in literaturevCongresses. 0aPlace (Philosophy) in literature. 0aSymbolismvCongresses. 0aSymbolism. 7aART / Environmental & Land Art.2bisacsh  aAi Wei Wei.  aAlbert Camus.  aAnthropocene.  aArcadia.  aAtomic Photographers Guild.  aAyuituq National Park.  aBarthes.  aBerlin.  aBrewery Pond.  aCOVID 19.  aCanada.  aCape Town.  aCezanne.  aChamolangma.  aChernobyl.  aChicago.  aColonus.  aDaiesh Refugee Camp.  aDavid McMillan.  aDistrict Six Museum.  aDonetsk airport.  aEdward Burtynsky.  aEverest.  aGroup Seven.  aHamish Fulton.  aHenry David Thoreau.  aHiroshima.  aIndian Residential School.  aIndigenous.  aJesper Svenbro.  aLa Peste.  aLesbos.  aManto.  aMargaret Olin.  aMark Ruwedel.  aMaurice Blanchot.  aMax Avdeev.  aMichel Foucault.  aMont St Victoire.  aMount Kailash.  aNagasaki.  aNational Socialism.  aNepal.  aNewfoundland.  aNora.  aNunavut.  aPalestine.  aPangnirtung.  aPaul Duro.  aPeter van Wyck.  aPort Hope.  aPoussin.  aQuAppelle Valley.  aRaymond Williams.  aRichard Long.  aRobert del Tredici.  aSaskatchewan.  aSebald.  aSophocles.  aTibet.  aWalden.  aWalter Benjamin.  aX marks spot.  aaesthetic.  aart.  aaura.  achorography.  acivic witness.  acolonialism.  acritical topography.  adisaster.  adocument.  aimitation.  ainscr